## Instructions

1. Execute the Five-Phase ReAct Loop from your system prompt.
2. **Auto-scope inference:** If `review_scope` is `full` (or unspecified):
   - All `.tsx` files under `frontend/components/` → infer `review_scope="ui_component_pr"`.
   - All files under `infra/dev-tier/` or `tests/infra/` → infer `review_scope="infra_audit"`.
   - All files under `middleware/` (Python) → narrow to FD9-only review (still `full` scope but FD1-FD7 dimensions skip with `status="skipped"`).
   Record the inference in `validation_log[0]` (e.g., `"Auto-inferred review_scope=infra_audit from file mix"`).
3. Run deterministic tools first for FD1, FD3, FD5, FD6, FD9, FD10, and the AST-detectable FD2/FD7 hypotheses on every applicable file. Apply LLM judgment only for residual FD2 (B6 Route Handler hygiene, U1 RSC suitability), FD4 appropriateness (always recorded as `gaps`, never findings), and FD8 stories whose `acceptance_signal` cannot be re-derived programmatically.
4. Produce a certificate for every hypothesis tested.
5. Apply the Judge criteria (Section 7) to filter findings.
6. Apply the strictest verdict decision rules (Section 8). Auto-reject anti-patterns (FE-AP-4, FE-AP-6, FE-AP-7, FE-AP-12, FE-AP-18, FE-AP-19), critical FD3 hypotheses (`CSP1`, `CSP2`, `SBX2`, `SEC1`, `SEC2`, `TRUST1`, `TRUST2`), and any critical FD9 (Middleware Ring) failure take precedence over count thresholds. FD8, FD10, FD11 add NO new auto-rejects — they inherit only when their hypotheses overlap an existing FD1/FD3 rule. List any auto-reject reasons inline at the top of the `statement` field.
7. Treat the items in the `Accepted V3 Deviations (do NOT flag)` subsection of `architecture_rules.j2` as canonical. Findings that contradict an entry in that list MUST be killed by the Judge gate (Section 7, Non-triviality).
8. Output a single `ReviewReport` JSON object as your final response.
